[{"location":"","page":"Reference","title":"Reference","text":"CurrentModule = MultiplesOfPi","category":"page"},{"location":"#MultiplesOfPi.jl","page":"Reference","title":"MultiplesOfPi.jl","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"","page":"Reference","title":"Reference","text":"Modules = [MultiplesOfPi]","category":"page"},{"location":"#MultiplesOfPi.Pi","page":"Reference","title":"MultiplesOfPi.Pi","text":"Pi\n\nThe number PiExpTimes(1, 1), numerically equivalent to pi. Using Pi instead of pi often produces results that avoid floating-point inaccuracies.\n\nExamples\n\njulia> sin(Pi)\n0.0\n\njulia> sin(π)\n1.2246467991473532e-16\n\njulia> exp(im*Pi) + 1 == 0\ntrue\n\njulia> exp(im*π) + 1 == 0\nfalse\n\njulia> (2//3)Pi + Pi == (5//3)Pi\ntrue\n\njulia> (2//3)π + π == (5//3)π\nfalse\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"constant"},{"location":"#MultiplesOfPi.PiExpTimes","page":"Reference","title":"MultiplesOfPi.PiExpTimes","text":"PiExpTimes(x, n)\n\nConstruct a number that behaves as x*π^n for a real x and an integer n\n\nExamples\n\njulia> PiExpTimes(2, 3)\n2Pi^3\n\nSee also: Pi\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"}]
